{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698267/1938030101/0550.xml":{"full_text":"8\n\u2018BIG THREE\u2019 JOIN\nTO BREAK JAM\nIN USED AUTOS'\nFord, Knudsen, Keller\nAct to End Depression\nDETROIT, March 1 (1.N.5.).\nEdsel Ford, William S. Knudsen\nand K. T. Keller today threw the\nweight of the motor industry\u2019s\n\u2022'Big Three\u201d behind the $1,250,000\nadvertising campaign to end the\nbusiness recession by breaking the\njam of used cars in the stocks of\ndealers.\nIn simultaneous statements\nthe first ever issued jointly by\nleaders of the Ford Motor Com\npany, General Motors Corporation\nand Chrysler Corporation\u2014the\nthree men pledged support of their\norganizations to the drive and ex\npressed the belief that a revival of\nautomobile production through a\nstimulated market would bring a\ngeneral business revival to the\nnation.\nINDUSTRY PRAISED i\nFord spoke of the industrv as a\nwhole, saying:\nThe one great contribution\nthe automobile industry made\nto the nation in its efforts to\nthrow off the last depression was\nits demonstration of courage in 1\nthe face of adversity. That\nsame fearlessness is evident to- I\nday as a united industry moves\nforward to start the wheels\nrolling again.\u201d 1\nKnudsen, head of the gigantic 1\nGeneral Motors Corporation, |i\nstressed the added highway safety i,\nthat will come with the junking\nof mechanically imperfect cars.\nHe said: I\n\"Spring is almost here, and I;\nthe cars that have been laid up\nduring the winter because of i\npoor condition are now ready\nto be traded. The industry\nwants to get these cars. It wants\nto furnish transportation at low 1\ncost and replace inefficient 1\nunits in away that will make\nthe purchasers satisfied and\nable to cover the road.\u201d\nEMPHASIES VALUE\nKeller, president of Chrysler 1\nCorporation, emphasized the car 1\nvalues of the present used-car\nmarket, saying:\n\u201cBoth engineering advances\nand improvements in manufac\nturing methods in recent years\nhave resulted in giving far more\nstrength and safety and longer\nlife to automobiles than the\noriginal owner will ever use.\n\u201cThe cars produced during\nthis period have been designed\ndeliberately not only for the\nfirst owner, but the possible\nsecond, third and fourth owners.\n\u201cThus, from the standpoint\nof intrinsic value, Chrysler Cor\nporation believes used cars of\nrelatively low mileage are bet-\nter automobiles than people\ngenerally realize.\u201d\nWidow Murdered,\nHome Is Robbed\nNEW YORK. March 1 (INS.). 1\nMurder for profit, executed with\nwanton brutality, was revealed to- j\nday with discovery of the body of\nMrs. Bessie Mersky, 65-year-old\nwidow, sprawled on the floor of\u201d\nher basement apartment in Brook-, 1\nlyn.\nHer skull had been crushed and\nthe killeu had trussed her hands\nand legs with rope. Every drawer\nin the flat had been pulled out\nand ransacked.\nCanada to Free\nThrashed Youths\nSANDWICH, Ont.. March 1 (I.N.\n5. \u2014Lashed 10 times each with a\nbroad five-tailed strap, two youths\nwho pleaded guilty to breaking\ninto the Patterson Collegiate Insti\ntute January 30 today were to be\nreleased from Sandwich Jail.\nThe youths, Robert Bell, 17. and\nGrant Famol, 16, who asked for\ntha lashing instead of a jail sen\ntence, were strapped yesterday m\nthe presence of their mothers.\nPolice Ordered\nTo Smoke \u2018Loco\u2019\nHAMILTON. Ont., March 1 (I.N.\n6, \u2014Hamilton police officers to\nday were ordered to take dope.\nPolice Chief E. K. Goodman issued\nthe orders yesterday, telling his\nmen to take a few whiffs of mari\nhuana cigarette smoke, so that\nthey will be able to detect the drug\nwhen they smell it.\nFOR BETTER HEATED HOMES\nUSE\nOUR FAMOUS\nREADING\nANTHRACITE\nCOAL\n|nc. i\n149 Rhode Island Ave. R. E.\nNOrth 1600\n\u2014for COAL or FUEL OIL\nTelephone RE publie 1234\nA. T. T. Income\n$9.76 Per Share\nNEW YORK. March 1\n(I.N.S. I.\u2014A merl ca n Tele\nphone and Telegraph Com\n-1 pany today reported net in\ncome for 1937 of $182,342,-\n000, or $9.76 a share, against\n$184,744,464, or $9.89, in 1938.\nThe company\u2019s common is on\na $9 annual dividend basis.\nOperating revenue for the\nentire Bell system increased\n5.7 per cent while operating\nexpenses advanced 8.9 jer\ncent, Walter S. Gifford, presi\ndent of the company, re\nported.\nGifford attacked the Fed\neral investigation of the Bell\nsystem as \"one sided\u201d and\ncharged that the company\n\u201cwas denied not only the\nright to cross-examine wit\nnesses and to be heard in its\nown behalf, but was denied\nthe right to have included in\nthe record written material\nwhich it had prepared and\nconsidered necessary to point\nout serious and important\nerrors affecting most of the\ninvestigators\u2019 reports.\u201d\nAIRLINER SETS\nSPEED RECORD\nAided by a tail wind that aver\naged 90 miles an hour, a Pennsyl\nvania-Central Airlines transport\nplane with a capacity load of 10\npassengers, today lowered the\nrecord flying time of transport\nplanes between Detroit and Wash\nington and bettered the schedule\ntime from Detroit by 58 minutes.\nPiloted by Al Brooks, veteran\ntransport pilot, the twin-engined\nBoeing monoplane landed at\nWashington Airport at 10:09 a. m.,\njust two hours and nine minutes\nafter the take-off from Detroit.\n[The scheduled flying time is three\n[hours and seven minutes.\nPilot Brooks also clipped his\nbest previous record from Pitts\nburgh. last stop on the Detroit-\nWashington run, by two minutes.\nThe time for this last leg of the\ntrip was 49 minutes. The sche\nduled time for this distance is\none hour and 10 minutes.\nAirport officials estimated the\nplane, built by the same concern\nthat manufactured the Army\u2019s\n\u201cflying fortress\u201d bombers, aver\naged 280 miles an hour on to\nday\u2019s record flight. After leaving\nDetroit, the plane stopped at\nCleveland and Akron before reach\ning Pittsburgh. Copilot of the\nplane was H. A. Simon.\nChinese Women\nGive Style Show\nCostumes of ancient China\nwere displayed at a fashion show\nheld at the Shoreham Hotel yes\nterday by the Chinese Women\u2019s\nAssociation, to raise funds for\ncivilian sufferers in the Sino-\nJapanese War.\nMany members of the diplo\nmatic corps and social leaders at\ntended the affair, at which eight\nyoung Oriental models displayed\nthe costumes. Among those taking\npart were Miss An-fu Wang,\ndaughter of the Chinese ambas\nsador. and Miss Hilda Yen, daugh\nter of the former ambasasdor,\nj who is now president of the Red\nCross of China.\n\u00a9Modern\nFUNERAL\nComplete\nwith Basket\n5 265\nJbRK including\nOVER\n'B B-J 60\n1 J Bfe ,Tm\nOF\nSERVICE\nW. W. CHAMBERS\nONI or THS\nLARGEST UNDERTAKERS\nIN THE WORLD\nQuality Buying Power\nMakes Possible\nQUALITY CASKETS\nATA 30%\nSaving to YOU\n\u2014fMITV\n1400 CHAPIN ST. N.W.\n517 llth ST. S. E.\nSIB CLEVELAND AVE.\nRIVERDALE, ND.\n$30,000 Stolen\nIn Maine Office\nAUBURN. Me.. March 1 (I.N.S.\nThe motor vehicles registry branch\noffice here has reported mys-jt\nterious disappearance of $30,000 f\nfrom the office safe during the'\nweek-end. i\nThe safe apparently had been\nopened by the combination and 1\nclosed again after the money was\ntaken. A window in the rear of\nthe office was open.\nTHE NATIONAL'S REMODELING SALE\n875,000 Worth of Furniture I\nl )lust Go to Make Room for Our H\nk New Men\u2019s, Women\u2019s Children\u2019s B\nCLOTHING DEPARTMENT I\n(To Open Within 30 Days) I\nW All Prices Slashed Some Below Cost!\nThere are no \"ifs,\" \"ands\" or \"buts\" about it\u2014we have simply got\n~jl/y. to make room for the builders to work. Prices have been slashed\nt 0 very bone \u2014many items being priced actually below costs,\npht/j u So come early and get your pick of the best values. No mer-\n\u25a0MI Kv 2 f chandise will be sold to dealers. Ilf\nINo Money Down! Trade-In Your Old Furniture!\ni\nI Reg. $64.95 Three-piece Bedroom Suite, Walnut Finish $39.95\nI Reg. $54.85 Three-piece Be